{"cursor":"3182","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":")]] 'Southern France' (or the 'south of France'), colloquially known as 'le\nMidi', {{cite book |title=Cycling guide to the Canal du Midi, Languedoc,\nFrance, Europe |first=Declan |last=Lyons |isbn=978-1-85284-559-9 |date=18\nFebruary 2009 |publisher=Midpoint Trade Books }} {{cite book\n|title=International French-English and English-French dictionary |first=Paul\n|last=Passy |isbn=  |publisher=Hinds, Noble &\nEldredge |year=1904 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yKBiAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA388-\n&lpg=PA388&dq=Le+Midi+mi+middle+and+di+day#v=onepage&f=false }} is defined\ngeographical area consisting of the regions of France that border the Atlantic\nOcean south of the Marais Poitevin , Spain, the Mediterranean, and\nItaly. The Midi includes: {{cite web |url=http://about-\nfrance.com/regions.htm#6 |publisher=about-france.com |accessdate=2009-09-18\n|title=The Regions of France - Midi (from the Pyrenees to the Riviera) |date=\n}} *Aquitaine *Midi-PyrÃ©nÃ©es *Languedoc-Roussillon *Provence-Alpes-CÃ´te\nd'Azur *Corsica *RhÃ´ne-Alpes (the Southern parts) *Poitou-Charentes (the\nSouthern parts) Louis Papy, Le midi atlantique, atlas et gÃ©ographie\nde la France moderne, Flammarion, Paris, 1984\n\nThis area corresponds in large part to Occitania; that to say, the territory in\nwhich Occitan () â as distinct from the of northern France â was historically\nthe dominant language. Though part of Occitania, the regions of Auvergne and\nLimousin are not normally considered part of the South of France.\n\nThe term Midi derives from mi (middle) and di (day) in Old French; compare\nMezzogiorno, the south of Italy. The time of midday was synonymous with the\ndirection of south because in France, as in all of the Northern Hemisphere, the\nsun is in the south at noon. The synonymy existed in Middle French as well,\nwhere can refer to both midday and south.\n","linknr":147,"url":"Southern_France","recorded":1371243040,"li